There are many pairs of function $P$ and $Q$ that satisfy the condition. Here's one solution:

$\begin{align}
P(x, y) &= x^3y^3 \\ \\
Q(x, y) &= \dfrac{4x^3y^3}{3}
\end{align}$

[[☃ explanation 1]]

Our final step is to find $\dfrac{\partial Q}{\partial x} - \dfrac{\partial P}{\partial y}$.

$\begin{align}
&Q_x = 0 \\ \\
&P_y = \dfrac{4x}{y} \\ \\
&\dfrac{\partial Q}{\partial x} - \dfrac{\partial P}{\partial y} = \dfrac{-4x}{y}
\end{align}$

Our final step is to find $\dfrac{\partial Q}{\partial x} - \dfrac{\partial P}{\partial y}$.

$\begin{align}
&Q_x = e^x \\ \\
&P_y = xe^{xy} \\ \\
&\dfrac{\partial Q}{\partial x} - \dfrac{\partial P}{\partial y} = e^x - xe^{xy}
\end{align}$
